"""
mkt-christ layer — 2 Corinthians all 13 chapters
Output: data/commentary/mkt-christ/2corinthians.json

2 Corinthians presents Christ as the Yes to all God's promises (ch1),
the new Moses of the new covenant (ch3), the firstborn of the new creation (ch5),
the reconciler (ch5), the generous one who became poor (ch8),
and the power made perfect in weakness (ch12).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "1": {
    "20": "<p>A direct revelation: 'All the promises of God find their Yes in him.' The entire prophetic, Abrahamic, and Davidic promise-system of the OT is ratified in Christ — he is not merely one who keeps promises but the one in whom the promise-structure itself is fulfilled. The 'Yes' is not merely verbal agreement but the constitutive reality of Christ's person and work: the covenant, the Servant mission, the Davidic throne, the new creation — all are 'Yes' in him. This is 2 Corinthians' opening Christological foundation before all the apologetics and ethics that follow.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "18": "<p>A direct revelation: 'We all, with unveiled faces, beholding the glory of the Lord, are being transformed into the same image from one degree of glory to another.' Moses saw YHWH's glory and came away with a fading reflected radiance; in Christ, every believer beholds the glory of God directly (John 1:14: we have seen his glory) and is progressively transformed into that same image. The Christological center: the image we are being transformed into is Christ himself (Rom 8:29: conformed to the image of his Son). The new covenant is therefore the transformation of believers into Christ-likeness — the goal of all Paul's ministry (Gal 4:19: until Christ is formed in you).</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "6": "<p>A direct revelation: 'God who said Let light shine out of darkness has shone in our hearts to give the light of the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ.' The glory of God — YHWH's Shekinah-presence, the consuming fire, the cloud-pillar, the heavenly radiance — is now specifically located: in the face of Jesus Christ. This is Paul's most explicit identification of Jesus with the divine glory. Conversion is a new-creation event (v. 6 echoes Gen 1:3) in which God's glory, once accessible only in the tabernacle and temple, is now encountered in the person of Christ.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "17": "<p>A direct revelation: 'If anyone is in Christ, new creation.' The eschatological new creation that Isaiah promised (Isa 65:17-25) is not merely a future cosmic event but a present reality for every person united to Christ. Christ is the embodiment of the new creation: his resurrection is the firstfruits of the new-creation body (1 Cor 15:20, 45); his Spirit is the down-payment of the new-creation life (2 Cor 1:22; 5:5). 'In Christ' is not merely a forensic status but a participatory location — to be in Christ is to be located within the sphere of the new creation that has already broken into the old age.</p>",

    "21": "<p>A direct revelation: 'For our sake he made him to be sin who knew no sin, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God.' The great exchange is the Christological ground of all Paul's soteriology: the sinless one (the one who 'knew no sin' in the experiential-relational sense of Heb 4:15) was made to be sin (took sin's full weight and consequence) so that those in him are made to be the righteousness of God. The substitution is complete and symmetrical: my sin became his; his righteousness becomes mine. Paul's atonement theology cannot be understood apart from this verse.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "9": "<p>A direct revelation: 'For you know the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, that though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor, so that you by his poverty might become rich.' Paul's appeal for the collection for Jerusalem is grounded in the Incarnation: Christ's voluntary self-emptying (becoming poor) for others is the prototype and motive for the Macedonians' and Corinthians' voluntary financial sacrifice for others. The Christological movement (rich → poor → rich for others) is the template for Christian generosity. This is the ethical application of the Christ-hymn logic (Phil 2:5-11): the self-giving of Christ generates the self-giving of his people.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "9": "<p>A direct revelation: 'My grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness.' The risen Christ speaks directly to Paul in response to three petitions. The Christological principle being enacted: Christ's power is not supplementary to human strength but is maximally displayed where human strength is absent. This is the Christological logic of the cross applied to Christian experience: just as God's power was manifested most fully in the apparent weakness of crucifixion, so Christ's power is manifested most fully through the apostle's weakness. The cross is not a one-time exception but the ongoing pattern of divine power-in-weakness.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH6 = {
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The apostolic co-working ('working together with him') is grounded in the ministry of reconciliation just defined (5:18-21). Paul and his team are co-laborers in Christ's ongoing reconciling work — the work of the one who 'reconciled us to himself through Christ' continues in apostolic proclamation. The appeal not to receive grace 'in vain' echoes the language of the Servant in Isa 49:4 ('I have labored in vain') — Christ as the Servant whose work could not fail means that the grace he accomplished cannot be emptied by the community's failure to respond. The appeal is urgent precisely because the reconciliation Christ achieved is real and available.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The 'favorable time' and 'day of salvation' from Isa 49:8 are now: Christ's death and resurrection have inaugurated the Servant's promised acceptable year. The eschatological 'now' (<em>nyn</em>) of the new covenant announces that the time for which Israel's prophets hoped has arrived in Christ. Every apostolic proclamation is a direct extension of the Servant's mission — Christ is both the fulfillment of the Isaianic acceptable-time and the one in whose name the apostle continues to declare it. The double 'now' (now is the acceptable time; now is the day of salvation) grounds the community's urgency in the Christological fulfillment of prophecy.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The concern to put 'no obstacle in the way of the gospel' identifies Paul's ministry conduct as subordinated to the message about Christ. The gospel's content (reconciliation through the crucified and risen Christ) must not be contradicted by the messenger's behavior. The Christological logic: a discredited apostle would suggest that the Christ he proclaims is likewise discredited. Authentic representation of the one who 'knew no sin' (5:21) requires a transparent ministry that does not invite accusations of corruption, exploitation, or deception.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The self-commendation 'as servants of God' through the hardship catalog places apostolic identity within the Christological pattern: the Christ who humbled himself and took the form of a servant (Phil 2:7) defines what genuine divine service looks like. Paul's hardship list is not masochism but Christological: the servant-pattern is the form authentic ministry takes in the world that crucified its Lord. The Corinthians who prize Sophistic display are being shown what Christ-shaped ministry actually looks like — not rhetorical triumph but endured suffering for the sake of others.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The catalog of beatings, imprisonments, tumults, labors, sleepless nights, and hunger reads against the backdrop of Christ's own passion: beaten, imprisoned, subjected to a tumultuous trial, laboring under the cross, forsaken in darkness. Paul's apostolic life is a participation in the sufferings of Christ (1:5: 'as we share abundantly in Christ's sufferings'). The hardships are not incidental to the apostolic mission but are the form in which Christ's suffering continues to be embodied in the world through those who belong to him and carry his message.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The virtues list — purity, knowledge, patience, kindness, Holy Spirit, unhypocritical love, word of truth, power of God — describes the character of Christ-shaped ministry. Each virtue reflects something of Christ's own character: the purity of the sinless one, the knowledge that comes through Christ (3:14; 4:6), the patience (makrothymia) of the one who endured the cross's shame (Heb 12:2), the kindness of the Lord whose yoke is easy (Matt 11:30). The Holy Spirit, through whom Christ distributes these virtues, is the link between Christ's character and the apostle's formed life.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The 'weapons of righteousness for the right and left hands' are the weapons of Christ's righteousness administered through apostolic ministry. In the Servant tradition (Isa 11:5: 'righteousness shall be the belt of his waist'), the Messiah is equipped with divine righteousness as his weapon. Paul wields not his own righteousness but Christ's — the same righteousness that the Corinthians have been made to be (5:21: 'the righteousness of God'). The apostolic defensive and offensive arming is a participation in the Messiah's own righteous warfare against sin, death, and the powers.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The antithetical pairs — honor/dishonor, slander/praise, deceivers/truthful — describe the mixed social reception of Christ himself projected onto his apostle. Christ was honored at his triumphal entry and dishonored at his crucifixion; praised as Messiah and slandered as a blasphemer; called a deceiver (Matt 27:63) and recognized as the Truth (John 14:6). The apostle's paradoxical social position is the continuation of the Christ-pattern: rejected by some, received by others, consistently misunderstood by those who evaluate by worldly standards.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The dying-yet-alive paradox of v. 9 is the resurrection pattern projected into the apostolic present. Christ was 'known' (acknowledged) and 'unknown' (rejected and misunderstood); he truly died and truly lives; he was disciplined (in the sense of suffering as the innocent one) yet not killed in any ultimate sense. Paul's apostolic experience is a participation in the dying-and-rising pattern of Christ: not mere imitation but genuine incorporation into the pattern of the crucified and risen one, whose death Paul carries in the body (4:10) and whose life is manifested through that death.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The 'having nothing yet possessing everything' is the eschatological reversal that Christ's resurrection inaugurates. The one who had 'nowhere to lay his head' (Matt 8:20) and was crucified in naked poverty possesses 'all things' (1 Cor 3:22-23; Col 1:15-20) as the risen and exalted Lord. Paul participates in both the poverty (literal economic vulnerability) and the possessing-all (the eschatological riches of the new creation that belong to those who are 'in Christ'). Christian poverty is not ultimate loss but participatory sharing in Christ's own redemptive movement through poverty to resurrection-wealth.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Paul's wide-open heart toward the Corinthians reflects the character of Christ's own open-hearted mission: the one who welcomed all who came to him, who 'opened wide his mouth' in proclamation (cf. Ps 81:10 LXX, cited with 'open your mouth and I will fill it'), whose heart was not restricted even toward those who rejected him. The apostle's emotional transparency (speaking 'plainly' — Corinthians, our mouth is open to you) is modeled on the directness of the Shepherd who calls his sheep by name and whose voice they recognize.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Corinthians' emotional narrowness toward Paul is a form of their narrowness toward Christ whom Paul represents. To restrict one's heart toward the apostle of reconciliation is to restrict it toward the reconciliation Christ accomplished. The relational repair Paul is urging has Christological stakes: the opened heart toward the apostle corresponds to the opened heart toward the one who 'stands at the door and knocks' (Rev 3:20 — to the Laodicean church, but applicable as a pattern). The Corinthians' return to Paul is the measure of their return to the Christ Paul embodies.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The father-children metaphor for apostolic relationship is rooted in Christ's own teaching about the heavenly Father and his children (Matt 6:9; John 20:17: 'my Father and your Father'). The apostle's fatherly appeal for widened hearts participates in the divine Father's own appeal to his people throughout Israel's history — an appeal the Son embodied in the incarnation. The request for reciprocal heart-widening is ultimately a request to receive Christ's own reconciling work fully: to let the love that was poured out through the cross do its complete work in the community's emotional life.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The prohibition against being unequally yoked with unbelievers is a Christological boundary: the community belongs to Christ, not to idols. The series of rhetorical contrasts (Christ/Beliar; believer/unbeliever; temple of God/idols) maps onto the cosmic conflict between Christ and the powers that Paul has described throughout. Christ's victory over the principalities and powers (Col 2:15) creates a community that belongs exclusively to him — participation in idol-cult worship would be a denial of that belonging, a practical assertion that Christ's lordship does not extend to every area of life.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The Christ/Beliar contrast is the eschatological conflict made concrete for the Corinthian community. Christ's exorcism ministry (Mark 1:21-28; 3:11-12) demonstrated his authority over all demonic powers; his death and resurrection completed the decisive defeat (John 12:31: 'now the ruler of this world will be cast out'). The community that belongs to the victorious Christ cannot share allegiance with the defeated powers. The absolute incompatibility Paul asserts is not cultural scrupulosity but Christological: Christ's lordship and Beliar's lordship are mutually exclusive, and the community must live in the reality of Christ's victory.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The 'temple of God' which the community is (cf. 1 Cor 3:16; 6:19) is the Christological transformation of the Jerusalem temple. Christ's body is the true temple (John 2:21: 'he was speaking about the temple of his body'); through union with him, the community becomes the dwelling-place of God in the Spirit. The covenant-formula citations that follow ('I will dwell in them... I will be their God') are the promises that Jesus claimed to fulfill when he cleansed the temple and declared it his Father's house. In Christ, the community is the new temple where God dwells among his people.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The call to 'come out and be separate' cites Isa 52:11 — the oracle that precedes the Fourth Servant Song (Isa 52:13-53:12). The Servant whose suffering is about to be described in Isa 53 is preceded by a call to the exilic community to depart from Babylon in purity. Christ is both the Servant whose suffering Isa 53 describes and the one whose departure from sin's domain (his incarnation as the sinless one who 'came out' from the Father, John 8:42) creates the community that is called out with him. Separation from idolatry is not legalism but participation in Christ's own holiness.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The expanded covenant-formula — 'I will be a father to you and you will be sons and daughters' — is fulfilled in Christ, who is the Son of God through whom believers become sons and daughters (Gal 4:4-7: God sent his Son... so that we might receive adoption as sons). The universal sonship-and-daughterhood Paul envisions (adding daughters to the original David-oracle) is grounded in the one Son who shares his Sonship with all who are united to him. The family of God is constituted by the Son's mediating work: because Christ is the Son, all who are in him share his filial relationship with the Father.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH7 = {
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The holiness-call — 'let us cleanse ourselves from every defilement of flesh and spirit' — is grounded in Christ's own work of purification. The letter to the Hebrews describes Christ as the high priest who purifies the conscience (Heb 9:14; 10:22); Peter calls believers who have been 'purified by obedience to the truth' (1 Pet 1:22). The new covenant promises written on hearts and put in minds (Jer 31:33, cited in Heb 8:10) are fulfilled in the Spirit who both motivates and enables the purification Paul calls for. 'Perfecting holiness in the fear of God' is the process by which Christ's own holiness is progressively formed in those who belong to him.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Paul's triple denial of wrongdoing — wronged no one, corrupted no one, exploited no one — parallels the sinlessness of Christ whom Paul represents. The apostle's integrity is a derivative expression of Christ's own faultless character: the one sent by Christ is to be as transparent and unblemished as the one who sent him. The Johannine parallel: 'as the Father has sent me, even so I am sending you' (John 20:21) — the integrity of the mission chain depends on the integrity of each link. Paul's blameless conduct is both a Christological obligation and a Christological testimony.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The solidarity expressed as 'you are in our hearts, to die together and live together' participates in the dying-and-rising solidarity that defines union with Christ. Paul is bound to the Corinthians with the same death-and-life solidarity that characterizes union with Christ: baptized together into his death, raised together in his resurrection (Rom 6:4-8). The apostle's personal loyalty to the community mirrors the depth of Christ's covenant loyalty — the Good Shepherd who dies for the sheep and then calls them by name in resurrection life (John 10:11, 14-16).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Paul's bold speech (<em>parrhēsia</em>) toward the Corinthians reflects the bold speech that characterized Christ's own ministry. Jesus taught 'as one having authority' (Matt 7:29), not as the scribes — a directness that astonished his hearers. John's Gospel repeatedly describes Jesus speaking 'plainly' (<em>parrēsia</em>, John 7:26; 10:24; 11:14; 16:25, 29) rather than in riddles. The apostle's confidence in speaking freely to his community is a participation in the frank, authoritative clarity of the one who is 'the Truth' (John 14:6) — speech shaped by that Truth and freed from the accommodating compromises that distort it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Fighting on the outside, fears on the inside' describes the totality of apostolic vulnerability — a vulnerability that participates in Christ's own experience. The Gethsemane prayer ('my soul is very sorrowful, even to death,' Matt 26:38) shows the one who bears all human anxiety; Paul in Macedonia with external conflicts and internal fears is living the Christological pattern where no anxiety is faced alone because the God of all comfort (1:3-4) meets every form of distress. The apostle's fearfulness is not unfaithfulness but the honest condition of those who carry the treasure of Christ in breakable clay jars (4:7).</p>",
    "6": "<p>God's comfort through Titus's coming is a specific instantiation of Christ's promise: 'I will not leave you as orphans; I will come to you' (John 14:18). The God who comforts the downcast comforts through personal presence — Titus's arrival embodies the presence-principle that Christ himself establishes. The comfort-chain (God → Paul through Titus → Corinthians) mirrors the Trinitarian chain of comfort: the Father comforts through Christ; Christ comforts through the Spirit; the Spirit comforts through community. Titus's arrival is a Christological event: the embodied presence of the comforter-God in the network of the body of Christ.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Corinthians' 'longing, mourning, and zeal' for Paul — reported through Titus — are the emotional fruits of genuine repentance that Christ's work of reconciliation produces. Where the gospel of reconciliation (5:18-21) is received, it transforms emotional life: longing replaces indifference, mourning replaces complacency, zeal replaces passivity. These are not manufactured religious emotions but the natural affective results of a genuine encounter with the Christ who wept over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41) and who gives his people hearts of flesh in place of hearts of stone (Ezek 36:26).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Paul's temporary regret about the painful letter reveals the humanity of apostolic ministry — a ministry modeled on the one who was 'made like his brothers in every respect' (Heb 2:17). Christ's apostle is not exempt from the emotional complexity of difficult relational interventions. But Paul's temporary regret was overridden by the transformative result: the godly grief produced repentance. The pattern mirrors Christ's own 'temporary' experience of desolation (Matt 27:46) that led to resurrection transformation — apparent pastoral defeat that God converts into deeper restoration.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The 'godly grief' that leads to repentance is the fruit of Christ's reconciling work reaching the Corinthians' hearts. The distinction between grief that produces repentance and grief that produces death is a Christological distinction: grief that leads toward Christ (who is the reconciliation) generates life; grief that turns inward or toward the world produces death. The Corinthians' godly grief is evidence that the Spirit of Christ (who convicts the world concerning sin, John 16:8) has been at work in them, converting their distress about the broken relationship with Paul into orientation toward the God of reconciliation.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The contrast between godly grief producing 'repentance unto salvation' and worldly grief producing 'death' is grounded in Christ's atoning work. The 'salvation' (<em>sōtēria</em>) into which godly grief moves is not generic moral improvement but the salvation Christ secured through his death and resurrection — the full restoration of the divine-human relationship that sin had fractured. 'Repentance' in the NT is specifically repentance toward God through Christ (Acts 20:21) — a turning whose destination is the reconciled relationship that Christ's cross makes available.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The seven fruits of godly grief — eagerness, defense, indignation, fear, longing, zeal, punishment — are evidence that Christ's reconciling work has reached the community's deepest levels. The Spirit who produces these results is the Spirit of the one who was 'eager' for the Father's will (John 4:34: 'my food is to do the will of him who sent me'), who feared God with appropriate reverence (Heb 5:7), and who through his death executed justice (<em>ekdikēsis</em>) on sin. The community's enacted repentance participates in and reflects the character of the one who bore the full weight of sin's consequences.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Paul's disclosure that the letter was written 'so that your care for us might be revealed to you' transforms what looked like a disciplinary crisis into a Christological revelation: the painful letter was a surgical instrument in the hands of the God who uses hardship to reveal what is in the heart (cf. Deut 8:2: 'to humble you, testing you to know what was in your heart'). The same principle operates in Christ's ministry: his challenging words and actions regularly revealed the hearts of his hearers — for healing those who were willing to be known and confronted by the Truth.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Titus's refreshed spirit from encountering the Corinthians is a participation in the joy of the Good Shepherd who finds the lost sheep (Luke 15:5-7). The comfort-chain (Corinthians comfort Titus; Titus's comfort comforts Paul) reflects the Spirit's work of building mutual encouragement through the body of Christ. Every genuine reconciliation in the community is an echo of the divine joy over the sinner who repents (Luke 15:7, 10) — the apostolic joy mirrors the heavenly joy over restored relationship, grounded in the one reconciliation that Christ's cross accomplished.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Paul's boast about the Corinthians proving true mirrors Christ's own faithfulness: the God who is faithful (1:18: 'as surely as God is faithful') keeps faith with his promises even when the human parties fail. Paul's confidence in the Corinthians was not naïve optimism but a faith rooted in the Christ who does not let his work fail (Isa 55:11; Phil 1:6: 'he who began a good work in you will bring it to completion'). The vindication of Paul's boast is simultaneously the vindication of the gospel's power: the word of reconciliation produces what it proclaims.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The Corinthians' reception of Titus 'with fear and trembling' echoes the eschatological reverence appropriate in the presence of divine grace. The same phrase ('fear and trembling') appears in Phil 2:12 as the manner of working out salvation — the godly awe before the God who works in us both to will and to work according to his good pleasure. When the community receives Christ's representative with appropriate reverence, they are expressing the reverence owed to Christ himself: 'whoever receives you receives me' (Matt 10:40). The Corinthians' welcome of Titus is a Christological act.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The closing declaration of complete confidence in the Corinthians — 'I rejoice that in everything I can have confidence in you' — anticipates the eschatological vindication of every Christ-community. Paul's confidence in the Corinthians, despite their many failures, is grounded in Christ's ongoing redemptive work in them: the one who intercedes for his people before the Father (Rom 8:34; Heb 7:25) ensures that the process of transformation will ultimately be completed. The joy of fully-restored confidence between Paul and the Corinthians is a foretaste of the final joy when the bride is presented without spot or wrinkle (Eph 5:27).</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH8 = {
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>The grace of God given in the Macedonian churches is grace flowing from Christ: 'the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ' (v. 9) is the source from which all human generosity springs. The collection is a christological act before it is a charitable act — the communities give because they have received the gracious gift of the one who 'though he was rich became poor.' Every gift in the collection is a downstream expression of the prior gift of the gospel: the grace of God that came in Christ (1:3-4; 4:15) overflows in human generosity toward the suffering poor.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Joy overflowing in the midst of severe suffering is the resurrection pattern applied to present experience: Christ's suffering issued in resurrection glory; the Macedonians' affliction issues in superabundant giving. The 'extreme poverty' that 'overflowed in wealth of generosity' mirrors the Christological logic of 8:9 — the poverty of the incarnation produced eschatological wealth for others. The Macedonians are living out the Christ-pattern without perhaps being aware of it: their giving enacts in concrete economics the incarnational logic of grace.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Giving 'beyond ability' and 'of their own accord' mirrors the voluntary, excess-giving of Christ: he was not obligated to become incarnate; he was not compelled to go to the cross; he gave beyond the minimum required. The apostolic appeal to Christ's example (v. 9) grounds all such voluntary super-giving in the prototype: the one who 'gave himself' (Gal 2:20; Tit 2:14) without external compulsion. The Macedonians' freedom in giving is a participation in Christ's freedom in self-giving — grace moving outward without calculating the cost.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Macedonians' request to participate in 'the service to the saints' frames financial giving as access to a form of Christ-service. The 'saints' are Christ's beloved community (those whom Christ loved and gave himself for, Eph 5:25); serving them materially is serving Christ in his members. Matt 25:35-40 makes this explicit: 'as you did it to one of the least of these my brothers, you did it to me.' The Macedonians' eagerness to give is an eagerness to serve Christ — they are asking for the privilege of participating in his ongoing ministry to his own body.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The decisive act — 'they gave themselves first to the Lord and then to us' — identifies the proper order of all giving: the prior self-gift to Christ makes every subsequent material gift an expression of that prior commitment. This mirrors the logic of the entire NT: the call to give possessions, money, time, and labor comes only after the call to give oneself to Christ in faith (Mark 8:34-35: 'if anyone would come after me, let him deny himself'). Material generosity without prior self-surrender produces philanthropy; material generosity flowing from prior self-surrender to Christ produces the new economy of grace.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Titus's role in bringing the collection to completion connects the practical financial work to the larger christological mission of reconciliation he has just accomplished (ch. 7). The same agent who helped restore the Corinthian community's relationship with Paul now facilitates the community's material expression of solidarity with Jerusalem. Reconciliation and generosity are inseparable in Paul's missional theology: genuine peace with God overflows in concrete solidarity with those who belong to God. The collection is the financial dimension of the reconciliation that Christ's cross established.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Paul's invitation to 'excel in this grace also' places generous giving in the same category as spiritual gifts: faith, speech, knowledge, earnestness, and love are all gifts of Christ through the Spirit (1 Cor 12:4-11); generosity is to be added to the list. The Christ-center of all gifts means that financial giving is not a separate category (secular) from spiritual gifts (sacred) but belongs to the same unified economy of grace. The 'abundance' in every spiritual respect should manifest in material abundance-for-others: the body of Christ shares the gifts its Head distributes.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The refusal to command — 'I say this not as a command' — mirrors Christ's manner of invitation rather than coercion. Christ called disciples with 'follow me,' not a legal compulsion; he invited the rich young man to voluntary dispossession (Mark 10:21) rather than demanding it. The gospel operates through freedom because its Author is the one who is himself free (John 8:36: 'if the Son sets you free, you will be free indeed'). Paul's gentle comparative appeal works with the grain of freedom that Christ's gospel creates, rather than producing obligated compliance through apostolic authority.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The completion of what was begun 'a year ago' is consistent with the Christological principle that Christ completes what he begins (Phil 1:6: 'he who began a good work in you will bring it to completion at the day of Jesus Christ'). The Corinthians' prior intention to give is a prior work of grace in them that now needs to be actualized. Paul's pastoral energy to help them complete what they began reflects Christ's shepherding commitment to follow through: the shepherd who found the lost sheep did not abandon it partway back to the fold (Luke 15:4-5).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Completion 'out of what you have' honors the Christological principle of proportional stewardship: Christ praised the widow who gave her two coins (Mark 12:43-44: 'she put in everything she had') while the gift is evaluated by the Giver who sees the heart, not by the observer who sees only the amount. The 'widow's mite' principle in Jesus's teaching grounds proportional giving in the God who evaluates by full commitment relative to capacity, not by absolute size of contribution. Paul's standard mirrors the Lord's own evaluation framework.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The acceptability of giving 'according to what a person has' reflects the character of God who accepts what is offered in genuine faith, not only what meets an impossible standard. The OT sacrificial principle — the poor could offer turtledoves rather than bulls (Lev 5:7; 12:8; cf. Luke 2:24) — established proportional giving as divinely acceptable. Christ's honoring of the widow's coins over the large temple donations (Mark 12:41-44) definitively established that God's evaluation is not by amount but by proportional whole-heartedness. Paul's pastoral accommodation participates in Christ's own generous evaluation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The principle of equality (<em>isotēs</em>) reflects the eschatological vision of the new creation in which the inequalities of the present age are overcome. Christ's own mission was directed toward the poor, the marginalized, and the excluded (Luke 4:18: 'the Spirit of the Lord is upon me... to proclaim good news to the poor'). The collection that moves resources from abundance to need is a partial, anticipatory enactment of the eschatological reversal: the last will be first; the poor inherit the kingdom; the hungry are filled with good things (Luke 1:52-53; 6:20-21). Christian giving is eschatological practice, not merely charitable administration.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The mutual-abundance exchange — Corinthian material surplus meeting Jerusalem's material need; Jerusalem's spiritual abundance having previously met Corinth's spiritual need — enacts the body-of-Christ interdependence that Christ established. Christ is the head of a body in which no member can say to another 'I have no need of you' (1 Cor 12:21). The Gentile communities received Israel's spiritual inheritance (the covenants, the promises, the Messiah, the Scriptures) and now return material support to the impoverished Jewish community. The collection is a concrete expression of the one-body reality that Christ's reconciling death (Eph 2:14-16) created.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The manna citation (Exod 16:18) applied to the collection invokes Christ as the true bread from heaven. Jesus in John 6:31-35 explicitly contrasts the manna ('he gave them bread from heaven to eat') with himself ('I am the bread of life'). The miraculous manna-equalization — each having exactly enough — is now the pattern for the Christ-community's economic life: the sufficiency that Christ provides becomes the sufficiency that the community circulates toward those in need. The collection is Eucharist-economics: as the bread of life is shared equally, so the community's material bread is redistributed toward equal sufficiency.</p>",
    "16": "<p>God putting 'the same earnestness for you' into Titus's heart mirrors Christ's own pastoral heart being extended through the Spirit into the apostolic co-workers. The earnest care Titus shows for the Corinthians is not Titus's own virtue but a divine gift placed in his heart — the same Good Shepherd's care that Christ expressed in his earthly ministry now extended through the Spirit into Christ's servants. Paul's thanksgiving to God for this gift identifies the source correctly: all genuine pastoral care flows from the one Shepherd whose voice the sheep recognize (John 10:3-4, 14).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Titus going 'of his own accord' — freely, voluntarily — is the Spirit's confirmation that this is a genuinely Spirit-led mission, not merely institutional compliance. The freedom-in-service pattern is Christological: Christ's 'no one takes my life from me; I lay it down of my own accord' (John 10:18) defines voluntary service as the mark of genuine Christ-following. When co-workers like Titus voluntarily embrace service and mission, they are following the pattern of the one who freely entered the incarnation, freely went to the cross, and freely gives his Spirit to those who are his.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The brother 'famous among all the churches for his preaching of the gospel' embodies the pattern of spreading fame through faithful service to the gospel rather than self-promotion. The gospel itself creates the reputation: those who faithfully serve its proclamation are recognized throughout the community of Christ's people. This contrasts with the opponents' approach (letters of recommendation from influential individuals); the apostolic community's recognition flows from visible, consistent gospel service — a community-wide witness to the quality of the work, not a paper credential from a social network.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The community appointment of delegates 'for the glory of the Lord himself' places the entire financial administration under the governance of Christ's honor. Every decision about how the collection is handled, who carries it, and how it is accounted for is evaluated by whether it glorifies the one in whose name the whole enterprise runs. The Christological criterion of glory replaces both the personal-reputation criterion (which drives self-promotion) and the mere-efficiency criterion (which might cut accountability corners). The collection serves Christ's glory before it serves the poor.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The concern that 'no one should blame us' reflects the gospel's stake in the apostle's financial integrity. The gospel of the one who 'knew no sin' (5:21) — who was transparent before the Father and before the world — must be carried by those whose financial conduct is beyond reproach. An apostle who mishandled donated funds would confirm every accusation that the gospel was merely a money-making scheme (cf. 2 Pet 2:3). The administrative accountability structures Paul builds into the collection are themselves a form of gospel witness: the community of the honest God practices honesty.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Aiming at what is honorable before the Lord and before people' applies Christ's double-standard of accountability to apostolic financial management. Jesus taught a unified ethical accountability: hidden deeds are seen by the Father who sees in secret (Matt 6:4, 6, 18) and will be disclosed publicly at judgment. The apostle who is accountable both to God (vertical) and to people (horizontal) is living in the integrity appropriate to the one who said 'I always do what is pleasing to him' (John 8:29) — complete transparency before the Father that has nothing to hide from human scrutiny either.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The twice-tested, repeatedly-proven brother reflects the Christological principle of tested character: the one who has been through trials and proven faithful is the reliable co-worker for Christ's mission. The testing and approval (<em>dokimazō/dokimos</em>) vocabulary runs through Paul's letters as a marker of genuine discipleship (Rom 12:2; 1 Cor 9:27; 2 Cor 10:18): Christ himself was 'tested in every way' (Heb 4:15) and proven faithful, establishing the pattern for those who carry his mission. The three-person delegation's tested character reflects the tested character of the commission they carry.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'The glory of Christ' as a description of the delegates is the highest possible identification: to see these messengers is to see Christ's honor made visible. The <em>shaliach</em> principle (the agent fully represents the sender) reaches its ultimate expression in Christ: 'whoever has seen me has seen the Father' (John 14:9). Those sent by Christ carry his representative presence; when the delegates bring the collection to Jerusalem, they are bringing a visible expression of Christ's own reconciling work — the Gentile church's material solidarity with the Jewish community as a concrete enactment of the 'one new man' that Christ created (Eph 2:15).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The appeal to 'show them the proof of your love' places Christian giving in the domain of covenant loyalty-demonstration. Love in the NT is not primarily an emotion but a covenantal commitment demonstrated in action (1 John 3:18: 'let us not love in word or talk but in deed and in truth'). Christ's own love was proven in the event of the cross (Rom 5:8: 'God shows his love for us in that while we were still sinners, Christ died for us'). The Corinthians' generous completion of the collection is a participation in that same demonstrated-love pattern: not merely affirming love verbally but putting it in concrete, costly, communal action.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH9 = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The service to 'the saints' (<em>hagioi</em>) places the collection in the framework of Christ's own service to his people. The language of 'service' (<em>diakonia</em>) applied to the collection echoes Christ's own self-description: 'the Son of Man came not to be served but to serve and to give his life as a ransom for many' (Mark 10:45). The Jerusalem saints are the recipients of service that flows from and mirrors Christ's own service. Every collection-gift is a downstream expression of the 'first service': the one gift of Christ that makes all subsequent Christian giving possible and shapes its character.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Paul's boasting about the Corinthians to the Macedonians — 'Achaia has been ready since last year' — participates in Christ's own intercessory role before the Father. The apostle who represents his communities before other communities mirrors the high-priestly work of the one who intercedes for his people (Heb 7:25; Rom 8:34). Paul's confidence in the Corinthians, expressed to the Macedonians, is the apostolic enactment of Christ's confidence in those who belong to him — the Good Shepherd who can say to the Father, 'those whom you have given me I have kept' (John 17:12).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The sending of delegates in advance 'so that our boasting about you may not prove empty' reflects the gospel's concern for community integrity. Christ's honor is tied to the character of those who bear his name: the communities that bear the name of Christ represent him to the watching world. When Paul's confidence in the Corinthians proves well-founded, it vindicates the gospel's transformative power. When communities fail, the name of Christ is maligned (Rom 2:24: 'the name of God is blasphemed among the Gentiles because of you'). The advance preparation protects Christ's honor by protecting the community's integrity.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The concern about social embarrassment before the Macedonians reflects the Christological stakes of community reputation. The community's public behavior — how it handles financial commitments, how it follows through on stated intentions — is a form of witness to the reliability of Christ's work in transforming lives. The community that fails to follow through on its gospel-commitments undermines the apostolic claim that Christ actually produces the transformation he promises. Paul's pastoral pressure is ultimately Christological: the honor of the gospel is at stake in whether the Corinthians complete what they promised.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The contrast between 'voluntary gift' (<em>eulogia</em>, blessing) and 'exaction' (<em>pleonexia</em>, covetousness) maps onto the distinction between the spirit of Christ and the spirit of the world. Covetousness — taking what belongs to others — is the anti-pattern of Christ who gave what belonged to himself. The collection processed as a blessing (freely given, genuinely generous, without obligation) becomes a Christological act: it reproduces the character of the gift that produced it. The 'blessing' framing echoes the OT concept of covenant blessing — giving that flows from receiving God's gracious gift participates in the blessing-economy Christ inaugurates.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The sowing-and-reaping principle anticipates the eschatological harvest that Christ's resurrection has made certain. The general resurrection as harvest (Matt 13:39: 'the harvest is the end of the age') frames all present sowing within the context of a guaranteed future reaping. The one who 'sowed' himself into the ground in death (John 12:24: 'unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains alone; but if it dies, it bears much fruit') has already demonstrated that generous sacrifice produces abundant harvest. Generous present-giving participates in the same sowing-for-harvest pattern that Christ's own death enacted.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'God loves a cheerful giver' reveals the character of the triune God: the Father who gives Christ (John 3:16: 'God so loved that he gave'), the Son who gives himself (Gal 2:20: 'who loved me and gave himself for me'), and the Spirit who generously distributes gifts (1 Cor 12:11). The divine love for the cheerful giver is a love for those who reflect the divine character of generous joy in giving. Reluctant or coerced giving does not reflect the character of the God who gives most when he gives himself — a gift not extracted by obligation but poured out from the overflowing abundance of Trinitarian love.</p>",
    "8": "<p>God's ability to make 'all grace abound to you' participates in the inexhaustible abundance of the divine giving that Christ reveals. The 'grace of our Lord Jesus Christ' (8:9) that Paul invokes as the prototype of generosity is not a depleting resource but an overflowing fountain: the self-giving God does not become less by giving. The divine autarkeia (self-sufficiency) that undergirds all human autarkeia is Christ's own fullness — 'from his fullness we have all received, grace upon grace' (John 1:16). God's provision for human giving is not a finite fund that might run out but an expression of the infinite self-giving that characterizes the triune life.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The 'righteousness that endures forever' cited from Ps 112:9 points forward to the permanent, eschatological righteousness that Christ's resurrection secures. Christ is 'our righteousness' (1 Cor 1:30); his righteousness does not fade or diminish (the 'fading glory' of Moses, 2 Cor 3:7, contrasts with the enduring glory of the new covenant). The giver whose generosity participates in the enduring divine righteousness is storing up 'treasure in heaven where neither moth nor rust destroys' (Matt 6:20) — giving whose eternal record is secured by the same righteousness that secures the giver's own standing before God.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The God who 'supplies seed to the sower and bread for food' will multiply the giving community's seed is the creator-God who sustains all life through Christ. 'All things were created through him and for him' (Col 1:16) — the agricultural cycle of seed-provision and harvest-multiplication is a Christological reality: the Logos through whom creation was ordered maintains its fruitfulness. When Paul invokes this God as the one who will 'increase the harvest of your righteousness,' he is pointing to the same creative and sustaining power that raised Christ from the dead as the guarantee of the collection's eschatological fruitfulness.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Enrichment 'in every way for every generosity' flows from the one who is 'the same yesterday and today and forever' (Heb 13:8) and who 'has blessed us in Christ with every spiritual blessing in the heavenly places' (Eph 1:3). The riches available for distribution are not the community's own finite resources but the inexhaustible riches of Christ (Eph 3:8: 'the unsearchable riches of Christ') that flow into the community and through it toward those in need. Every generous act of the community is an occasion for thanksgiving to God because every act of generosity traces back to the one inexhaustible source.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The collection's dual function — supplying the saints' physical needs and generating thanksgiving to God — reflects the two dimensions of Christ's own ministry: meeting physical need (feeding the multitudes, healing the sick) as a sign of the coming kingdom, and directing all thanksgiving to the Father. Every act of service in Christ's name both meets a concrete need and makes a theological claim: the God who provides is the God of Israel, the Father of the Lord Jesus Christ, whose character is generous faithfulness. The collection is liturgical because it enacts and makes visible the economy of grace that Christ established.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The Jerusalem community's 'glorifying God for your obedience to the confession of the gospel' identifies the collection as a confessional act. The Corinthians' giving demonstrates that their verbal confession ('Jesus is Lord') has produced the bodily obedience that genuine confession requires. The gospel of reconciliation (5:18-21) is not merely a message about what Christ did but a reality that reshapes every dimension of community life, including economics. The Jerusalem community's praise of God for Gentile generosity fulfills the eschatological vision: 'they will bring the wealth of the nations to you' (Isa 60:5) enacted through the body of Christ.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Jerusalem's prayer for the Corinthians 'because of the surpassing grace of God upon you' identifies the Corinthians' giving as an evidence of divine grace, not human achievement. Christ's grace is 'surpassing' (<em>hyperballousa</em>) — exceeding all normal human boundaries and expectations. When the Jerusalem community prays for the Corinthian Gentiles who have given sacrificially, they are praying for those whom God's grace has reached across the ethnic and geographic boundaries that previously separated them. The collection has created a bond of prayer and mutual recognition across the Jewish-Gentile divide that Christ's cross established in principle (Eph 2:14-16).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The doxological close — 'thanks be to God for his inexpressible gift' — identifies the ultimate context of the collection: the gift that cannot be described fully is Christ himself, whose self-giving generates all subsequent giving and whose resurrection guarantees all future harvest. The entire discourse on the collection (chs. 8-9) is enclosed between two doxologies (8:16; 9:15), both giving thanks to God. The collection is not an interruption of the theological letter but its practical enactment: the truth that God gave his inexpressible gift in Christ generates the concrete practice of inexpressible generosity in those who receive him.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH10 = {
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Paul's appeal 'by the meekness and gentleness of Christ' invokes Christ's own self-description: 'I am gentle and lowly in heart' (Matt 11:29). The incarnate Lord's manner of dealing with those he came to restore was not forceful imposition but patient invitation — 'he will not break a bruised reed' (Isa 42:3, cited in Matt 12:20). The apostle who appeals in Christ's character rather than in apostolic authority mirrors the one who washed his disciples' feet (John 13:4-5) and called the weary to himself with a gentle yoke. Christ-shaped authority is always servant-authority, even when that authority includes the capacity for sharp confrontation (vv. 2-6).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Paul's desire not to have to 'be bold against' those who accuse him of walking 'according to the flesh' reflects the apostolic preference for the power of persuasion over the power of confrontation. Christ's own pattern included both gentle invitation (Matt 11:28-30) and sharp confrontation (Matt 23:1-36); the measure was always the other person's capacity for growth, not the teacher's preference for comfort. The Christological critique of 'walking according to the flesh' is decisive: the apostle whose ministry conforms to Christ's pattern of kenotic weakness-and-power is operating according to the Spirit, regardless of how it appears to those who evaluate by Sophistic standards.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The distinction between 'living in the flesh' and 'waging war according to the flesh' mirrors Christ's own incarnational paradox: 'the Word became flesh' (John 1:14) — Christ lived fully in the flesh — yet his weapons were not fleshly but spiritual. The cross itself was the supreme example of anti-fleshly warfare: what appeared to be defeat-by-flesh (crucifixion) was actually decisive victory over the powers (Col 2:15: 'he disarmed the rulers and authorities... triumphing over them in him'). Paul's ministry reproduces this pattern: apparent weakness operating through divine power that the flesh cannot perceive or counter.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The weapons of apostolic warfare that have 'divine power to destroy strongholds' are the weapons Christ himself employed: truth against deception (John 8:32: 'the truth will set you free'), the Spirit against the powers (Luke 11:20: 'by the finger of God I cast out demons'), and the gospel against every form of spiritual bondage. Christ's ministry was itself a warfare — the binding of the strong man (Matt 12:29) so that his house could be plundered; the apostle continues this same campaign through the proclamation of the same gospel. The weapons are 'divine' because they are Christ's own weapons extended through the apostolic mission.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Taking every thought captive to the obedience of Christ' identifies Christ as the Lord and goal of all intellectual life. The mind that is 'set on the Spirit is life and peace' (Rom 8:6); the renewed mind 'discerns what is the will of God' (Rom 12:2). Every argument and every lofty opinion that resists 'the knowledge of God' is ultimately a refusal to acknowledge Christ's lordship — the same refusal that brought the powers to crucify 'the Lord of glory' (1 Cor 2:8). The apostolic work of demolishing intellectual pretension and bringing thoughts under Christ's authority is the extension of Christ's own claimed lordship over every domain of human life and thought.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The readiness to 'punish every disobedience when your obedience is complete' reflects the eschatological judgment pattern: Christ delays his final judgment until the full number of his people is gathered (2 Pet 3:9; Rom 11:25-26). The sequence — complete the community's obedience first; then address the recalcitrant minority — mirrors the divine patience that waits for the full harvest before the separation (Matt 13:28-30: let the wheat and tares grow together until the harvest). Christ-shaped discipline works with the community's growth rather than against it, timing judgment to serve restoration rather than satisfy immediate justice-demands.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'If anyone is confident he is Christ's' — the claim of belonging to Christ is the fundamental Christian identity claim. Paul's symmetrical response ('so also are we') refuses to let the opponents define what being 'Christ's' looks like by Sophistic standards. The crucified and risen Christ does not recruit based on rhetorical impressiveness; his community includes 'not many wise according to worldly standards, not many powerful, not many of noble birth' (1 Cor 1:26). Being 'Christ's' is defined by the cross, not by the Sophists' criteria — the apostle who carries the cross's message in suffering and weakness is as authentically 'Christ's' as any impressive rhetorician claims to be.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Authority given 'for building up and not for tearing down' reflects Christ's own stated purpose: 'I came that they may have life and have it abundantly' (John 10:10). The Son of Man who came not to condemn but to save (John 3:17; 12:47) sets the pattern for all apostolic authority: it serves the community's flourishing, not the authority-holder's status. When apostolic authority must confront and discipline, it does so in service of the community's ultimate building-up — the same logic as Christ's 'hard sayings' that challenged in order to save. Authority exercised for one's own advantage distorts the Christ-pattern into its opposite.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Paul's concern about appearing to 'frighten by letters' reflects the gentleness-in-authority that characterizes Christ's manner. Christ warned the scribes and Pharisees in devastating language (Matt 23) but never used fear as a tool for manipulation — his severe words aimed at repentance and restoration, not at consolidating his own power. Letters that intimidate without pastoral purpose fail the Christological test: the apostle's written authority, like Christ's spoken authority, must always serve the recipients' good rather than the author's dominance. The difference between Paul and a threatening bully is precisely this: the goal is always the community's freedom and flourishing.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The criticism — 'his bodily presence is weak and his speech contemptible' — was directed against Christ himself: 'Is this not the carpenter's son?' (Matt 13:55); 'Can anything good come out of Nazareth?' (John 1:46); 'He is a friend of tax collectors and sinners' (Luke 7:34). The social dismissal of the Messiah on the basis of his unimpressive origins and associations is reproduced in the dismissal of his apostle on the basis of his unimpressive physical presence and rhetoric. Christ chose not to come in royal splendor but in vulnerable human form; Paul's 'weakness' is therefore a Christological credential, not a disqualification.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The consistency between letter and deed, absent and present, reflects the integrity of Christ who is 'the same yesterday and today and forever' (Heb 13:8). The Christological standard of consistency — the same character whether before the crowds or alone, whether before friends or enemies, whether triumphant or suffering — is the standard Paul claims to meet. The contrast with the opponents is unstated but implied: those who are impressive only in certain performance contexts lack the Christological consistency of the servant-apostle whose authority is always for the community's good in every context.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The folly of self-referential comparison — 'comparing themselves among themselves' — is the opposite of the Christological standard of evaluation. The Christ who is 'the image of the invisible God' (Col 1:15), the perfect revelation of divine glory, is the standard against which all apostolic character is measured. The opponents who use their own network as the measurement system are operating in a closed self-referential loop that has cut them off from the only measurement that matters: conformity to Christ. Paul's appeal to the divinely-assigned <em>kanōn</em> points away from peer-comparison to the theological standard that Christ himself embodies.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The <em>kanōn</em> (sphere/rule) that God assigned to Paul is ultimately derived from Christ's own commission: 'Go and make disciples of all nations' (Matt 28:19) — the apostolic territory is defined by the risen Lord's mandate, not by human networking or social capital. Paul's refusal to boast beyond the limits of his assigned sphere is a form of Christological obedience: the servant does not exceed the assignment of the master. The geographic expansion of the mission westward is under the same divine ordering — each step is within the territory Christ is claiming through his apostle's pioneer preaching.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Paul's claim to have 'come all the way to you with the gospel of Christ' is the apostolic enactment of Christ's own 'going' mandate. Christ's commission ('you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem, in all Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the earth,' Acts 1:8) is being progressively fulfilled through Paul's westward mission. Corinth — the major commercial hub of Greece, on the crossroads between East and West — represents a strategic step toward 'the ends of the earth.' Paul's presence in Corinth is not accidental geographical coincidence but the result of Christ's guidance of the mission (cf. Acts 16:6-10: the Spirit directing Paul's travel).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The hope that 'as your faith grows, our area may be greatly enlarged among you' places the community's spiritual maturation in service of the mission's geographic expansion. This mirrors Christ's pattern: as the disciples grew in faith and understanding, they were given greater responsibility in the mission (John 15:15-16: 'I have called you friends... and appointed you that you should go and bear fruit'). The Corinthians' faith-growth is not merely for their personal benefit but for the enlargement of Christ's territory — their stability enables the frontier to be pushed further west toward the ends of the earth.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The commitment to preach 'in lands beyond you' without 'boasting of work already done in another's field' reflects the logic of Christ's own pioneer-mission: he was sent to the lost sheep of the house of Israel (Matt 15:24) as the first step in the mission that would eventually reach the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8). Paul's refusal to build on another's foundation participates in the same logic: the pioneer apostle always goes where Christ has not yet been named, because the unreached are the ones who most urgently need the gospel. The western horizon is where the pioneer-mission of Christ's apostle must go.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Let the one who boasts boast in the Lord' applies Jer 9:23-24 christologically: the Lord in whom believers boast is identified in Paul's usage as the Lord Jesus Christ (cf. 1 Cor 1:31, where the same citation concludes the argument that Christ is 'our wisdom, righteousness, sanctification, and redemption'). The prophetic word redirects all human glory-competition toward Christ: he is the only worthy object of boasting because he alone is the source of every genuine achievement. The entire apostolic controversy of ch. 10 resolves into this: Paul's only boast is in the Christ he proclaims, not in the territory he covers or the impressiveness of his rhetoric.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'The one whom the Lord commends' is approved (<em>dokimos</em>) — and Christ is the ultimate Commender. At the final judgment, the verdict 'well done, good and faithful servant' (Matt 25:21, 23) is the only commendation that ultimately matters. All the letter-recommendations, community praise, and rhetorical reputation that the opponents display are penultimate credentials that the divine evaluation will either confirm or overturn. The apostle who has been sent by Christ, who has served in Christ's character, and who has built Christ's community can await that eschatological commendation — the only approval worth having.</p>"
  }
}

